A Small Scheme VM, Compiler, and REPL in 4K

A Small Scheme VM, Compiler, and REPL in 4K

Samuel Yvon, Marc Feeley

VMIL 2021

VM Design Tradeoffs

  • A VM is designed to select an acceptable combination of the following properties:
    1. Speed of execution
    2. Memory usage while executing
    3. Footprint of the executable
    4. Portability
  • Typical system chooses 1/2
  • We target the extreme end of 3/4

Why?

Several use cases for small VMs:

  • Microcontrollers (limited memory space)
  • Embedded languages and scripting
    • Low footprint embedding in other systems
    • Portability allows code reuse accross many platforms
  • Web Apps (fast download)
  • Low overhead embedding in documents (html, pdf, xls)

Producing an Executable

Ribbit

  • Multiple implementations
    • C
    • JS
    • Python
    • Scheme
  • AOT compiler : rsc.scm + library files
  • Compiled code runs on the rVM

Why Scheme?

  • Small specification
  • Extensible
  • Compiled programs can be abstracted in few VM primitives
  • However, Some non-trivial features:
    • Tail-Call optimizations
    • First-class continuations
    • Garbage Collection

Runtime libraries

  • Two flavors:
    • min supports necessary features
    • max supports most of R4RS procedures (no I/O)
  • Full REPL implementation:
    • Implies some IO primitives

Design: Basic Data Representation

  • Data organized in a “rib”, a 3 field structure
  • Fields can be:
    • A reference to a rib
    • A native integer
  • Universal and versatile data structure:
    • Chainable through any field
    • Program source is a linked chain of ribs
    • Stack is also a linked chain of ribs
    • Complex chaining possible

Design: Code Representation

Design: Garbage Collection

  • Rely on host’s garbage collector if possible
  • Otherwise, implementation of Cheney-style “Stop & Copy”
  • Implemented in the C virtual machine
    • Requires a tagged representation of integers to distinguish with rib reference
